 {"id":"bd-17p2","title":"huh: Fix MultiSelect cursor position mismatch with filtering","description":"# Bug: MultiSelect Cursor Position Mismatch with Filtering

## Problem Statement
In the MultiSelect view() method, cursor position calculation is incorrect
when filtering is active:

```rust
// Line 2231 in lib.rs
fn view(&self) -> String {
    let filtered = self.filtered_options();  // Returns filtered indices
    let visible: Vec<_> = filtered.iter().skip(self.offset).take(self.height).collect();

    for (i, (idx, opt)) in visible.iter().enumerate() {
        let is_cursor = self.offset + i == self.cursor;  // BUG HERE
        // ...
    }
}
```

## Root Cause Analysis
The problem is index space confusion:

1. `self.cursor` is an index into the UNFILTERED options list
2. `filtered` contains indices into the unfiltered list
3. `visible` is a slice of the filtered list
4. `self.offset + i` is an index into the FILTERED list

When comparing `self.offset + i == self.cursor`, we're comparing
filtered-space index with unfiltered-space index.

## Example
Options: [A, B, C, D, E] (indices 0-4)
Filter: "C" matches only C at index 2
filtered = [(2, C)]
visible = [(2, C)]
self.cursor = 2 (pointing to C in unfiltered list)
self.offset = 0
i = 0

is_cursor = (0 + 0 == 2) = FALSE  // Wrong! C should be highlighted

## Expected Behavior
The cursor should highlight C because self.cursor (2) matches
the filtered item's original index (also 2).

## Solution Design
Compare against the original index from the filtered list:

```rust
for (i, (idx, opt)) in visible.iter().enumerate() {
    // Compare cursor with the original index, not the view position
    let is_cursor = *idx == self.cursor;
    // ...
}
```

Alternatively, if cursor should track filtered position:
```rust
// When filtering changes, remap cursor to filtered space
fn apply_filter(&mut self) {
    let filtered = self.filtered_options();
    // Find position of current cursor item in filtered list
    self.cursor = filtered.iter()
        .position(|(idx, _)| *idx == self.cursor)
        .unwrap_or(0);
}
```

## Implementation Steps
1. Determine intended behavior: cursor tracks item or position?
2. Fix the comparison in view()
3. Update navigation to work correctly with filtered indices
4. Add tests for filtering + cursor interaction

## Testing Strategy
```rust
#[test]
fn multiselect_cursor_position_with_filter() {
    let mut ms = MultiSelect::new(vec!["Apple", "Apricot", "Banana", "Cherry"]);

    // Move cursor to "Banana" (index 2)
    ms.cursor = 2;

    // Apply filter "a" (matches Apple, Apricot, Banana)
    ms.filter_value = "a".to_string();
    ms.update_filter();

    // Cursor should still highlight "Banana"
    let view = ms.view();
    assert!(view.contains("▸ Banana") || view.contains("> Banana"));
}

#[test]
fn multiselect_cursor_adjusts_when_filtered_item_hidden() {
    let mut ms = MultiSelect::new(vec!["Apple", "Banana", "Cherry"]);
    ms.cursor = 1;  // Banana

    // Filter hides Banana
    ms.filter_value = "c".to_string();  // Only Cherry matches
    ms.update_filter();

    // Cursor should adjust to valid position
    assert!(ms.cursor == 0 || /* cursor points to Cherry */);
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Cursor correctly highlights intended item when filtered
- [ ] Navigation (up/down) works correctly in filtered state
- [ ] Cursor adjusts gracefully when filtered item is hidden
- [ ] No regression in unfiltered behavior
- [ ] Tests cover filter + cursor interaction","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-01-28T02:19:39.853210637Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-01-28T02:19:39.874727937Z","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["cursor","filtering","huh","multiselect"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-17p2","depends_on_id":"bd-2xzk","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-01-28T02:19:39.874689556Z","created_by":"ubuntu"}]}
